  "objectives": "Objectives â€” Improve BAC through previously learned control and performance concepts and demonstrate limited proficiency with local departure and recovery procedures, communication standards, and straight in procedures in the local pattern and at unfamiliar airfields.\r\nAccomplish the following:\r\nUse part task features to increase exposure to multiple straight in scenarios.\r\nStudents demonstrate a minimum of limited proficiency in departure and recovery procedures, and radio procedures.\r\nIntroduce the ILS in the context of it being an instrument-based straight in. Do this as a part task from outside the FAF on final approach course or dogleg. Discuss descending at the FAF as a reference to a defined range/altitude on glidepath. Practice flying the final portion of the ILS. The intent is to relate control and performance concepts for maintaining a stable, approx. 3-degree glidepath between visual and instrument straight ins, and not to focus on the specifics of instrument approach setup or procedures.\r\nIf student proficiency allows, all items should be introduced by Q2002.\r\nQ2003 should not normally introduce new maneuvers, but is available for additional practice for students whose proficiency did not allow for satisfactory accomplishment of all items by Q2002.",
